    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i've also been hearing a lot of people say that originalism is basically just a way for certain judges to push a specific political agenda under the guise of law. how do scholars respond to that criticism? is it considered a legitimate way to interpret things or more of a political tactic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scholars who defend originalism argue that it is a rigorous, objective methodology, not a political tool, because it seeks historical accuracy. They maintain that adhering to the original public meaning is a neutral standard, unlike living constitutionalism, which allows for subjective judicial activism. Critics often accuse originalists of selectively choosing historical evidence to fit their desired outcomes, which is a common critique of any historical interpretation. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether one views constitutional interpretation as a scientific pursuit of meaning or a political act of modern policymaking.",
      "source": "target",
