    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the breakdown. so if the goal is to avoid \"subjective judicial activism,\" wouldn't an originalist approach actually be more problematic in practice? i mean, if the original meaning is vague or doesn't address modern tech or society, doesn't that basically force judges to just make up their own rules anyway while pretending they're being \"neutral\"? it feels like it just creates a loophole for bias.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are hitting on the central weakness of the originalist position, which is often framed by its detractors. When the text is ambiguous, originalism forces judges into a difficult position where they must either apply an outdated understanding or engage in heavy historical reconstruction. Critics argue that in the face of modern realities, clinging rigidly to 18th-century understandings forces judges to make decisions that are functionally arbitrary, thus becoming a form of masked activism. Therefore, while the *intent* is to prevent bias, the *practice* can easily devolve into judicial fiat when the original text fails to anticipate contemporary issues.",
      "source": "target",
